  'ba62e153-fa45-4d83-9c03-66f80b01a675',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$C# Async/Await — What the State Machine Is Actually Doing$escape$,
  $escape$Every `async` method in C# gets compiled into a state machine by the compiler. When you `await` an incomplete `Task`, the method suspends, returns control to the caller, and resumes on a captured `SynchronizationContext` (or `ThreadPool` if none exists). This is cooperative, not preemptive — no goroutine scheduler, no OS thread per coroutine.

Unlike Go's goroutines (M:N green threads with a runtime scheduler) or Java's virtual threads, C# async/await is purely callback-based under the hood — the `IAsyncStateMachine` drives the continuations manually. No thread is blocked during an `await` on I/O; the `ThreadPool` thread is released and reassigned.

For CPU-bound parallelism, `Task.Run()` offloads to the `ThreadPool`. For actor-like patterns, `System.Threading.Channels` gives you typed, backpressured message passing without a framework. `Parallel.ForEachAsync` (introduced in .NET 6) handles bounded concurrency over async workloads cleanly. Avoid `async void` outside event handlers — exceptions escape the `Task` graph and crash the process silently.$escape$,
  $escape$using System.Threading.Channels;

var channel = Channel.CreateBounded<int>(capacity: 100);

// Producer
var producer = Task.Run(async () => {
    for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++)
        await channel.Writer.WriteAsync(i);
    channel.Writer.Complete();
});

// Consumer — no thread blocked, no actor framework needed
var consumer = Task.Run(async () => {
    await foreach (var item in channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync())
        Console.WriteLine(item);
});

await Task.WhenAll(producer, consumer);$escape$,
