INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '73f9a4a1-3e06-4105-91ef-e8df57f382c5',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$C# Security — Memory Safety, Injection Prevention, and Dependency Scanning$escape$,
  $escape$C# is memory-safe by default — the GC-managed heap prevents buffer overflows. But `unsafe` blocks and `stackalloc` reintroduce those risks. Every `fixed` pointer dereference and manual `MemoryMarshal.CreateSpan` call bypasses runtime bounds checks; audit them carefully. Prefer `Span<T>` and `Memory<T>` for stack-local slices — they enforce bounds by default.

SQL injection most commonly enters through EF Core's `FromSqlRaw`, which accepts raw string concatenation. Use `FromSqlInterpolated` instead — it wraps interpolated values in `DbParameter` automatically, never embedding them as literals. For Dapper, always use anonymous-object parameters, never string concatenation.

For dependency vulnerabilities, `dotnet list package --vulnerable --include-transitive` queries the NuGet vulnerability database (backed by GitHub Advisory). Transitive dependencies are where CVEs hide — the `--include-transitive` flag is non-negotiable. The command returns a non-zero exit code on findings, making it CI-compatible out of the box. Pair it with `dotnet outdated` (global tool) to surface unmaintained packages before they become attack vectors.$escape$,
  $escape$// UNSAFE: raw interpolation — SQL injection risk
var bad = ctx.Users
    .FromSqlRaw($"SELECT * FROM Users WHERE Email = '{userInput}'")
    .ToList();

// SAFE: FromSqlInterpolated wraps values in DbParameter
var good = ctx.Users
    .FromSqlInterpolated($"SELECT * FROM Users WHERE Email = {userInput}")
    .ToList();

// CI gate — fails build if any vulnerable package found
// dotnet list package --vulnerable --include-transitive$escape$,
  $escape$csharp$escape$,
