INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '3ffc7b0c-694c-47e2-bf5c-688100554013',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$C# Horizontal Scaling — What the ThreadPool and async/await Actually Mean for Your Architecture$escape$,
  $escape$ASP.NET Core scales horizontally well, but only if you understand what's happening under the hood. Kestrel uses a small pool of I/O threads paired with the CLR ThreadPool. When a request awaits an async I/O operation — `await dbContext.SaveChangesAsync()`, `await httpClient.GetAsync(...)` — the thread is returned to the pool, not blocked. This means 10 ThreadPool threads can serve thousands of concurrent requests, making stateless pods behind a load balancer cheap to scale.

The trap: mixing sync-over-async (`Task.Result`, `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()`) blocks ThreadPool threads, causing starvation under load. With 8 CPUs, you exhaust threads fast. Use `ConfigureAwait(false)` in library code to avoid deadlocks on SynchronizationContext.

For true horizontal scale, enforce statelessness: move session to Redis (`IDistributedCache`), avoid in-process singletons that hold mutable state, and use `IHttpContextAccessor` carefully across async boundaries. Sticky sessions are a scaling anti-pattern — if your pods aren't interchangeable, adding more doesn't help. `CancellationToken` propagation across all async calls ensures graceful pod shutdown during rolling deploys.$escape$,
  $escape$// Bad: blocks a ThreadPool thread under load
var result = dbContext.Users.ToListAsync().GetAwaiter().GetResult();

// Good: thread returns to pool while awaiting I/O
var result = await dbContext.Users.ToListAsync(cancellationToken);

// Stateless distributed cache — safe across pod replicas
public class UserSessionService(IDistributedCache cache)
{
    public async Task SetAsync(string userId, UserSession session, CancellationToken ct)
    {
        var json = JsonSerializer.Serialize(session);
        await cache.SetStringAsync(userId, json, new DistributedCacheEntryOptions
        {
            AbsoluteExpirationRelativeToNow = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(30)
        }, ct);
    }
}$escape$,
