INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '353d0f64-f759-458d-b8ea-3e129179eae8',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$C#'s Ecosystem Maturity — Why NuGet's 350K Packages Are Only Part of the Story$escape$,
  $escape$C#'s ecosystem isn't just large — it's institutionally backed. Microsoft ships first-party libraries for nearly every backend concern: `Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection`, `Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore`, `System.Text.Json`, and `Microsoft.Extensions.Http` (typed `HttpClient` with Polly-style resilience via .NET 8's `AddStandardResilienceHandler`). These aren't community afterthoughts — they're versioned alongside the runtime and carry LTS guarantees.

For cross-cutting concerns, the community fills gaps with high-quality, stable libraries: Dapper (lightweight SQL mapping, 17M+ monthly downloads), MediatR (in-process CQRS), FluentValidation, Serilog, and AutoMapper all follow semantic versioning and maintain changelogs. NuGet's package signing and `dotnet list package --vulnerable` integrate directly into CI to catch deprecated or CVE-flagged dependencies.

Long-term viability is anchored by the .NET Foundation and Microsoft's public roadmap. .NET 8 is an LTS release (supported until November 2026), giving teams a stable target. The `global.json` file pins SDK versions per repo, eliminating 'works on my machine' drift across teams. C#'s ecosystem maturity means fewer abandoned dependencies and more predictable upgrade paths than most ecosystems.$escape$,
  $escape$// Pin SDK version + audit dependencies in CI
// global.json
{
  "sdk": { "version": "8.0.404", "rollForward": "latestPatch" }
}

// Check for vulnerable packages
// dotnet list package --vulnerable --include-transitive

// Built-in resilience (no extra package needed in .NET 8)
builder.Services.AddHttpClient<GitHubClient>()
    .AddStandardResilienceHandler(); // retry + circuit breaker + timeout

// Dependency injection — zero third-party libs needed
builder.Services.AddScoped<IOrderService, OrderService>();$escape$,
  $escape$csharp$escape$,
